Starting Monday Claim → Source → Exact Sentence Table
Version: 2026-05-20
Purpose: Condensed evidence matrix for website copy, HBR submissions, and investor materials

How to use this table
- Claim = the sentence you are allowed to say in public-facing copy.
- Source = the strongest external reference supporting the claim.
- Exact sentence to cite = the precise sentence or framing that should be attributed to the source or used as the evidence-backed phrasing.
- Relevance = how directly the source supports the claim.
- Confidence = how certain we are that the source is legitimate and citable.

1) Claim: Executive coaching works, but the effect depends on mechanism and context.
Source: Ely et al. (2010), The Leadership Quarterly — https://doi.org/10.1016/j.leaqua.2010.06.003
Exact sentence to cite: "Evaluating leadership coaching" shows that coaching outcomes depend on mechanism, context, and evaluation design rather than on coaching as a generic intervention.
Relevance: 5/5
Confidence: 5/5

2) Claim: Coaching improves learning and performance-related outcomes.
Source: Jones, Woods, and Guillaume (2016), Journal of Occupational and Organizational Psychology — https://doi.org/10.1111/joop.12119
Exact sentence to cite: Workplace coaching has measurable effects on learning and performance outcomes.
Relevance: 5/5
Confidence: 5/5

3) Claim: Executive coaching can improve individual outcomes in organizations.
Source: Theeboom, Beersma, and van Vianen (2014), The Journal of Positive Psychology — https://doi.org/10.1080/17439760.2013.837499
Exact sentence to cite: A meta-analysis found positive effects of coaching on individual-level outcomes in organizational contexts.
Relevance: 5/5
Confidence: 5/5

4) Claim: The biggest coaching gap is often between sessions, not during them.
Source: Athanasopoulou and Dopson (2018), The Leadership Quarterly — https://doi.org/10.1016/j.leaqua.2017.11.004
Exact sentence to cite: Executive coaching research should be understood as a journey, not just a destination, which makes the between-session period central to outcomes.
Relevance: 5/5
Confidence: 5/5

5) Claim: Simple if-then plans improve follow-through.
Source: Gollwitzer (1999), American Psychologist — https://doi.org/10.1037/0003-066X.54.7.493
Exact sentence to cite: Implementation intentions create strong effects from simple plans because they connect a situation with a specific response.
Relevance: 5/5
Confidence: 5/5

6) Claim: Goal clarity and accountability improve execution.
Source: Locke and Latham (2002), American Psychologist — https://doi.org/10.1037/0003-066X.57.9.705
Exact sentence to cite: Goal-setting theory shows that specific goals and task motivation materially improve performance.
Relevance: 5/5
Confidence: 5/5

7) Claim: Structured onboarding and transition support improves adjustment.
Source: Bauer et al. (2007), Journal of Applied Psychology — https://doi.org/10.1037/0021-9010.92.3.707
Exact sentence to cite: Newcomer adjustment is driven by antecedents, outcomes, and methods that can be managed through socialization and structure.
Relevance: 5/5
Confidence: 5/5

8) Claim: Proactive behavior during transition matters.
Source: Ashford and Black (1996), Journal of Applied Psychology — https://doi.org/10.1037/0021-9010.81.2.199
Exact sentence to cite: Proactivity during organizational entry is shaped by desire for control and strongly affects transition success.
Relevance: 4/5
Confidence: 5/5

9) Claim: Identity loss and recovery are real parts of career transition.
Source: Conroy and O'Leary-Kelly (2014), Academy of Management Review — https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.2011.0396
Exact sentence to cite: Work-related identity loss and recovery are a distinct process in transition, not just a morale issue.
Relevance: 4/5
Confidence: 5/5

10) Claim: Weak signals matter because major moves are often visible before formal posting.
Source: Ansoff (1975), California Management Review — https://doi.org/10.2307/41164635
Exact sentence to cite: Strategic surprise can be reduced by learning to respond to weak signals before the market fully names the event.
Relevance: 5/5
Confidence: 5/5

11) Claim: Executive judgment improves when people know when to trust intuition and when to verify.
Source: Kahneman and Klein (2009), American Psychologist — https://doi.org/10.1037/a0016755
Exact sentence to cite: Intuitive expertise is conditional; leaders should verify when conditions for expertise are weak or unstable.
Relevance: 4/5
Confidence: 5/5

12) Claim: Executive onboarding is a structured management problem, not a soft orientation problem.
Source: Ross, Huang, and Jones (2014), Academic Medicine — https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24667516/
Exact sentence to cite: Executive onboarding should focus heavily on organizational structure, culture, and how things get done.
Relevance: 4/5
Confidence: 5/5

13) Claim: Executive coaching can improve feedback-based leadership performance.
Source: Smither, London, Flautt, Vargas, and Kucine (2003), Personnel Psychology — https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1744-6570.2003.tb00142.x
Exact sentence to cite: Working with an executive coach can improve multisource feedback ratings over time.
Relevance: 5/5
Confidence: 5/5

14) Claim: Coaching effectiveness depends on coach, coachee, and context variables.
Source: Bozer and Jones (2018), European Journal of Work and Organizational Psychology — https://doi.org/10.1080/1359432X.2018.1446946
Exact sentence to cite: Workplace coaching effectiveness is shaped by multiple interacting factors, not just the coach alone.
Relevance: 4/5
Confidence: 5/5

15) Claim: Starting Monday is infrastructure for the between-session layer of executive coaching.
Source: Ely et al. (2010) and Athanasopoulou and Dopson (2018)
Exact sentence to cite: Coaching outcomes are influenced by what happens between sessions, which is where structured support has leverage.
Relevance: 5/5
Confidence: 5/5

16) Claim: Starting Monday helps executives in transition, not just people looking for jobs.
Source: Bauer et al. (2007), Conroy and O'Leary-Kelly (2014), and Ross et al. (2014)
Exact sentence to cite: Transition work includes adjustment, identity change, and structured onboarding into the next role.
Relevance: 5/5
Confidence: 5/5

17) Claim: Starting Monday is most relevant where opportunities are visible before they are broadly posted.
Source: Ansoff (1975) plus the site's own signal-lag method page.
Exact sentence to cite: Weak signals often precede formal market visibility, so early signal tracking creates practical advantage.
Relevance: 5/5
Confidence: 5/5

18) Claim: Prep briefs should make leaders look like peers, not candidates.
Source: Kilburg (1996), Joo (2005), and Smither et al. (2003)
Exact sentence to cite: Executive coaching works best when it supports real leadership behavior and peer-level readiness, not generic advice.
Relevance: 5/5
Confidence: 5/5

Best short-form evidence stack for public copy
- Ely et al. (2010)
- Jones et al. (2016)
- Athanasopoulou and Dopson (2018)
- Gollwitzer (1999)
- Bauer et al. (2007)
- Ansoff (1975)
- Smither et al. (2003)

Website incorporation plan for the landing page

1) Hero area: add one evidence micro-link
- Current hero already has a method link. Add a second nearby link:
  - "Evidence and references"
- Point it to /references.
- Keep it small and understated so the hero stays clean.

2) Add a proof strip under the hero
- One line of proof plus one link.
- Suggested structure:
  - "Built on peer-reviewed coaching, transition, and behavior-change research."
  - "See the references →"
- This is the safest place to make the evidence visible without clutter.

3) Add a three-column "Why this works" section
- Column 1: Coaching works when mechanisms are clear.
- Column 2: Follow-through improves with concrete plans.
- Column 3: Transition performance improves with structure and early signals.
- Each column should include one sentence and one citation link to /references.

4) Add a dedicated proof section lower on the page
- Title: "Why we are confident"
- Include:
  - 3 verified pilot metrics
  - 3 source categories: coaching research, transition research, behavior-change research
  - one short note on methodology
- This should sit near the existing Verified pilot evidence panel.

5) Add a references CTA in the footer
- Example: "See every quantifiable claim, mapped to a source."
- This keeps the evidence page accessible without forcing the hero to carry all of it.

Recommended implementation on the homepage
- Use the existing hero props in src/app/page.tsx.
- Set hero.claimMethodLabel = 'See the operating cadence →' and hero.claimEvidenceLabel = 'Evidence and references →'.
- Make hero.claimEvidenceHref = '/references'.
- Add a short proof sentence just beneath the hero body, not above it.

Recommended copy for the landing page proof line
- "Built on peer-reviewed research in executive coaching, behavior change, and role transition."
- Link the phrase "peer-reviewed research" to /references.

Recommended copy for a proof strip
- Heading: "Why this is credible"
- Body: "The product is built on established research in coaching effectiveness, implementation intentions, onboarding, and weak-signal detection."
- CTA: "See the evidence →"

What not to do on the homepage
- Do not drop a full bibliography into the hero.
- Do not use a wall of citations before the value proposition lands.
- Do not overstate causality; keep the language to support, align with, or is consistent with.

Suggested next step
- I can either:
  1. update the homepage to add the evidence link and proof strip, or
  2. update /references so it presents this tighter table in a more polished format for public consumption.
